    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "When conducting physical surveillance during a fraud investigation, which legal consideration presents the greatest liability risk for fraud examiners?",
      "tag": "Surveillance",
      "options": [
        "A. Failing to obtain written consent from the surveillance subject before commencing monitoring activities",
        "B. Violating reasonable expectation of privacy by conducting surveillance in areas where privacy is legally protected",
        "C. Using surveillance equipment without first obtaining proper licensing from regulatory authorities",
        "D. Conducting surveillance outside normal business hours without supervisory approval"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Per CFE Manual 2024, surveillance must respect reasonable expectation of privacy. Intrusion into legally protected private areas violates tort law and constitutional protections, exposing examiners to civil liability and evidence exclusion. Public areas generally lack privacy expectations.",
      "justification_wrong": "Consent is not required for lawful surveillance in public areas. Equipment licensing and business hours are not primary legal considerations. The critical factor is whether surveillance intrudes upon areas where subjects have legitimate, legally recognized privacy expectations.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "fraud_investigation/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
