      "num": 2,
      "text": "When conducting physical surveillance during a fraud investigation, what legal consideration takes precedence in most jurisdictions?",
      "tag": "Surveillance - Legal Considerations",
      "options": [
        "A. Reasonable expectation of privacy standards determining permissible observation locations and methods",
        "B. Obtaining written consent from all individuals who may be observed during surveillance",
        "C. Securing court-issued warrants before commencing any form of physical surveillance",
        "D. Limiting surveillance activities exclusively to public business hours between 9 AM and 5 PM"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "CFE Manual 2024 emphasizes reasonable expectation of privacy as the primary legal standard. Surveillance in public spaces where no reasonable privacy expectation exists is generally permissible, while observing private areas requires authorization. This balances investigative needs with privacy rights across jurisdictions.",
      "justification_wrong": "Written consent (Option B) defeats surveillance purposes; warrants (Option C) aren't universally required for public observation; time restrictions (Option D) lack legal basis. The reasonable expectation of privacy test provides the fundamental framework for determining surveillance legality and appropriateness.",
