        "D": "The investigator only needs to obtain the client's written authorization to conduct the undercover operation"
      },
      "correct_answer": "B",
      "explanation": "Covert operations by private investigators involve complex legal considerations including: recording consent laws (one-party vs two-party states), reasonable expectation of privacy even in semi-public spaces, restrictions on using false pretenses to obtain information, and property rights. While retail spaces are semi-public, employees may still have privacy expectations, and pretexting regulations (like the Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act) restrict deceptive practices. Option A oversimplifies recording laws; Option C is incorrect as private investigators can conduct undercover work within legal bounds; Option D is insufficient as client authorization doesn't override statutory or ethical requirements. Investigators must assess all applicable laws and regulations before conducting covert operations.",
      "topic": "Covert Operations",
      "sub_topic": "Undercover Investigations - Legal Framework",
