    {
      "question": "A CFE is conducting a covert investigation into suspected fraud at a manufacturing facility. Which of the following actions would be MOST appropriate when using an undercover operative?",
      "options": [
        "Have the operative record all conversations without consent to maximize evidence gathering",
        "Ensure the operative does not engage in any illegal activity or encourage others to commit crimes",
        "Instruct the operative to create documents that appear to implicate the suspects",
        "Direct the operative to access the company's computer systems using another employee's credentials"
      ],
      "correct_answer": 1,
      "explanation": "When using undercover operatives in fraud investigations, it is critical that the operative does not engage in illegal activity or act as an agent provocateur by encouraging others to commit crimes. The operative should observe and document activities naturally occurring, not manufacture evidence or entrap individuals. Recording conversations without consent may violate wiretapping laws in many jurisdictions. Creating false documents would constitute fabrication of evidence. Accessing computer systems using another's credentials could violate computer fraud and unauthorized access laws. The operative must maintain legal and ethical boundaries while gathering information.",
